value.value: A metabolic metabolic disorder characterized by excess urinary excretion of the purine base xanthine.
A synpolydactyly that is not part of a larger syndrome.
A speech disorder characterized by frequent sound or syllable repetitions, sound prolongations, or other dysfluencies that are inappropriate for the individual's age.

definition.value: Editor note: check this; consider subclass for familial

value.value: A language disorder characterized by difficulty in language acquisition despite otherwise normal development and in the absence of any obvious explanatory factors.
A scoliosis with no known cause.
A muscular dystrophy which begins at the lower legs and affects the shoulder region earlier and more severely than distal arm.
The drooping of the upper eyelid.
A mitochondrial oxidative phosphorylation disorder in which multiple mitochondrial respiratory chain complexes.

A rare developmental defect of the eye characterized by usually bilateral absence of the normal protrusion of the cornea from the sclera, the corneal curvature being the same as that of the adjacent sclera. Most patients develop hyperopia, hazy corneal limbus, and arcus lipoides at an early age. The condition may present as an autosomal dominant or an autosomal recessive form, with the latter showing more severe signs and symptoms (such as a round and opaque thickening located centrally in the cornea) and more frequent association with other ocular anomalies.
A pigmentation disease characterized by reticulate hyper- and hypo-pigmentated macules in a generalized distribution.
Inflammation of the uvula.

An upper respiratory tract disease characterized by the unusual growth of the adenoid tonsil; has symptom snoring, has symptom hyponasality, has symptom otitis media with effusion, has symptom mouth breathing.
Inflammation of the skin at the corners of the mouth characterized by redness, fissures or crusts.

An epithelial hyperplasia of the oral cavity mucosa associated with Epstein-Barr virus and found almost exclusively in persons with HIV infection. The lesion consists of a white patch that is often corrugated or hairy.
A bacterial, fungal or parasitic abscess that develops in the lung parenchyma. Causes include aspiration pneumonia, necrotizing pneumonia, necrotizing malignant tumors, and Wegener's granulomatosis.
Cessation of breathing and/or cardiac function.
Inflammation of the mucosal lining of the mastoid antrum and mastoid air cell system of the mastoid process.
A breast disease characterized by a collection of pus in the breast.
A tooth disease characterized by a localized collection of pus associated with a tooth.
A polyp that arises from the surface of the cervix.
An intestinal disorder characterized by an opening in the anal canal to the perianal skin. In the vast majority of cases there is a history of perianal abscess.
An abnormal pregnancy in which the conception is implanted outside the endometrial cavity.
An embryonal rhabdomyosarcoma located in the parameningeal region.

definition.value: Editor note: check subclasses, does not appear to be complete

value.value: An osteoporosis caused by chronic glucocorticoid use. Glucocorticoids impair the replication, differentiation and function of osteoblasts and induce the apoptosis of mature osteoblasts and osteocytes; the also favor osteoclastogenesis leading to an increase in bone resorption.
A condition that is caused by infection with Bartonella, and which is characterized by vascular proliferation, usually in immunocompromised individuals.

label.value: syndrome caused by partial chromosomal deletion

value.value: A chromosomal disorder consisting of the absence of a part of a chromosome.

definition.value: Editor note: this is used in DOID to encompass typically partial deletions

label.value: syndrome caused by partial chromosomal duplication

value.value: A chromosomal disorder consisting of the presence of a part of a chromosome in more copies than in a regular genome.

definition.value:
This term includes partial trisomy (one additional copy of a chromosome part), and partial tetrasomy (2 additional copies of a chromosome part).

Editor note: this is used in DOID to encompass typically partial duplications

value.value: Any corneal dystrophy (disease) in which the cause of the disease is a mutation in the TGFBI gene.
A corneal dystrophy (disease) that involves the corneal epithelium.
A respiratory system disease with a basis in a pathological type I hypersensitivity reaction.
An autoimmune form of peripheral neuropathy.

definition.value: Editor note: We do not draw a distinction between between neuropathy and peripheral neuropathy see https://github.com/NCI-Thesaurus/thesaurus-obo-edition/issues/20

value.value: Immunologically mediated adverse reactions to medicinal substances used legally or illegally.
A allergic disease that involves the digestive tract.

Allergic reaction to products containing processed natural rubber latex such as rubber gloves, condoms, catheters, dental dams, balloons, and sporting equipment. Both T-cell mediated (hypersensitivity, delayed) and IgE antibody-mediated (hypersensitivity, immediate) allergic responses are possible. Delayed hypersensitivity results from exposure to antioxidants present in the rubber; immediate hypersensitivity results from exposure to a latex protein.

A severe, rapidly fatal reaction occurring most commonly in children following an infectious illness. It is characterized by large, rapidly spreading skin hemorrhages, fever, or shock. Purpura fulminans often accompanies or is triggered by disseminated intravascular coagulation.

label.value: anomalous left coronary artery from the pulmonary artery

value.value: A congenital coronary vessel anomaly in which the left main coronary artery originates from the pulmonary artery instead of from aorta. The congenital heart defect typically results in coronary artery fistula; left-sided heart failure and mitral valve insufficiency during the first months of life.
A disease involving the vertebral column.
Pathological conditions of the cardiovascular system caused by infection of mycobacterium tuberculosis. Tuberculosis involvement may include the heart; the blood vessels; or the pericardium.
An acute B-lymphoblastic leukemia occurring in adults.
A specific developmental disorder that is characterized by physical, behavioral and learning birth defects resulting from maternal ingestion of nicotine during pregnancy.
A rare neural tube defect during pregnancy, resulting in the absence of a large portion of the brain and skull in the fetus.

A disorder characterized by malformations in the structure of the capillaries in the brain. It is caused by mutations in the CCM2, KRIT1 and PDCD10 genes. The capillaries fill with blood and stretch, thereby creating cavernous spaces. Some patients experience headaches, seizures, or visual and hearing disturbances. Cerebral hemorrhage may also occur.
Infections with bacteria of the genus salmonella.
The formation of a blood clot in the lumen of a vessel or heart chamber; causes include coagulation disorders and vascular endothelial injury.
A bone disease that results in formation or resorption abnormalities located in bone.
